      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies for the confusion. Let's talk about sulfur and lime without the goblin references. Sulfur is used to lower the pH of the soil, making it more acidic, which can help if your soil is too alkaline. Lime, on the other hand, raises the pH, making the soil more alkaline, which is beneficial if your soil is too acidic.\n\nWhen using either sulfur or lime, it's important to follow the instructions carefully. Over-application can indeed harm your plants. Start with a small amount, as recommended on the product label, and then retest the soil pH after a few weeks to see if further adjustments are needed. It's like seasoning a dish; a little goes a long way, and you don't want to overpower the flavors. Always err on the side of caution and make gradual changes to avoid shocking your plants. With the right balance, your tomato plants should be able to recover and thrive.",
